        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/>
                Phila.&#44; Wednesday&#44; Aug. 15<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#44; 1883.<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Father&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>We received your postal from<lb/> Albany this morning&#44; and were glad to hear that<lb/> you were all right&#44; despite the inconveniences of<lb/> travel.  We are all doing well&#44; and expect to get<lb/> along nicely.  I enclose you two letters&#45;&#45;one<lb/> arrived the same day you left&#44; and is&#44; doubtless&#44;<lb/> from Pareare&#59; the other I received from Mr. Polano<lb/> last evening&#44; when at his house to make arrangements<lb/> about the Synagogue services.  I will read the<lb/> Friday Evening &#38; <hi rend="underline">Mussaf</hi> services &#38; perhaps&#44; the prayer<lb/> for the government&#59; he&#44; the rest.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mr. Joseph Mendes of 149 N. 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.&#44;<lb/>&#45;&#45;one of our Friday evening <hi rend="underline">tenors</hi>&#45;&#45;wishes you<lb/> to write a letter&#44; or certificate&#44; addressed to the<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Parnassim</hi> of the Spanish &#38; Portuguese Congregation<lb/> of Amsterdam&#44; Holland&#44; stating that he &#40;Mendes&#41;<lb/> is alive &#38; resides at the above address in this city&#44;<lb/> is married to Sarah Gabrielle Perevia Mendoza&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>by whom he has two &#40;2&#41; children.  His<lb/> object is &#40;so he states&#41; to receive a certain<lb/> sum allotted half yearly&#44; on his wife&#39;s ac&#45;<lb/>&#45;count&#59; she <del>was an</del> being an orphan has a<lb/> claim thereto.  this is&#44; as far as I can<lb/> understand.  Please write the certificate as<lb/> soon as possible&#44; &#38; send it to me.  It must<lb/> arrive in Amsterdam&#44; one month prior to<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Rosh Hashana</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>I saw Jones this &#40;Wednesday&#41; mor&#45;<lb/>&#45;ning.  I will&#44; most likely&#44; spend next week<lb/> from Sunday to Friday at his cottage in Atlantic<lb/> City.  I suppose Cousin Josephine &#40;who returns<lb/> tomorrow &#40;Thursday&#41;&#41; will stay with the children<lb/> meanwhile.<lb/></p>
            <p>That fellow&#44; Stein of Wilkesbarre&#44;<lb/> has been poking fun &#91;&#63;&#93; at those who observe the<lb/> Feast of Ab.  Some rigamarole of his appeared<lb/> in one of his city dailies.  Jones will have something<lb/> to say about him this week.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think I have told you about all.<lb/>  Inquiring friends send their kind regards.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>With love from all.<lb/>  Your son&#44;<lb/> Henry.<lb/></p>
            <p>To the<lb/> Rev. S. Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S.&#45;&#45;I send by this mail Tuesday&#39;s &#38; Wednesday&#39;s <hi rend="underline">Ledger</hi>&#44; &#38;<lb/> I will mail other papers&#44; as desired.  Brace sent you his &#34;time&#34;<lb/> article in the daily <hi rend="underline">Record</hi>.  I put it&#44; together&#44; with 2 <hi rend="underline">Archives Israelites</hi>&#44; in<lb/> your desk.  Have heard nothing yet from Sonneschein.  Will wait until<lb/> Friday&#44; as he may be induced to write owing to his not having received<lb/> the regular monthly letter from me to the <hi rend="underline">Jewish Tribune</hi>.<lb/></p>
        </body>
